{"parse":{"title":"Minimalism (technical communication)","pageid":13064721,"revid":859930311,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Minimalism</b> in <a href=\"/wiki/Structured_writing\" title=\"Structured writing\">structured writing</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Topic-based_authoring\" title=\"Topic-based authoring\">topic-based authoring</a>, and technical writing in general is based on the ideas of <a href=\"/wiki/John_M._Carroll_(information_scientist)\" title=\"John M. Carroll (information scientist)\">John Millar Carroll</a> and others. Minimalism strives to reduce interference of information delivery with the user's sense-making process. It does not try to eliminate any chance of the user making a mistake, but regards an error as a teachable moment that content can exploit.\n</p><p>Like <a href=\"/wiki/Robert_E._Horn\" title=\"Robert E. Horn\">Robert E. Horn</a>'s work on <a href=\"/wiki/Information_mapping\" title=\"Information mapping\">information mapping</a>, John Carroll's principles of Minimalism were based in part on cognitive studies and learning research at Harvard and Columbia University, by <a href=\"/wiki/Jerome_Bruner\" title=\"Jerome Bruner\">Jerome Bruner</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Jerome_Kagan\" title=\"Jerome Kagan\">Jerome Kagan</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/B.F._Skinner\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"B.F. Skinner\">B.F. Skinner</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/George_Armitage_Miller\" title=\"George Armitage Miller\">George A. Miller</a>, and others. Carroll argues that training materials should present short task-oriented chunks, not lengthy, monolithic documentation that tries to explain everything in a long narrative.\n</p><p>A historian of technical communication, <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=R._John_Brockmann&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"R. John Brockmann (page does not exist)\">R. John Brockmann</a>, points out that Fred Bethke and others at IBM enunciated task orientation as a principle a decade earlier in a report on IBM Publishing Guidelines.\n</p><p>Carroll observes that modern users are often already familiar with much of what a typical long manual describes. What they need is information to solve a task at hand. He feels that documentation should encourage them to do this with a minimum of systematic instruction.\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/Darwin_Information_Typing_Architecture\" title=\"Darwin Information Typing Architecture\">Darwin Information Typing Architecture</a> (DITA) is built on Carroll's theories of Minimalism and Horn's theories of Information Mapping.\n</p><p>Minimalism is a large part of <a href=\"/wiki/JoAnn_Hackos\" title=\"JoAnn Hackos\">JoAnn Hackos</a>' recent workshops and books on information development using structured writing and the DITA <a href=\"/wiki/XML\" title=\"XML\">XML</a> standard.\n</p><p>Good writing means that the message is directly clear to the projected audience. Adopting a minimalist method may appear, in the short-term, to cost more, as writers must cut up and rephrase content into single free-standing chunks. However, the longer-term brings cost-saving benefits, particularly in translation and localization, where often sum is on a \u2018per word\u2019 basis. But the greatest advantage for companies is user fulfillment. The less time a customer spends working out how to do something, the more likely they are to purchase again.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Minimalism_(technical_communication)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>IBM Publishing Guidelines (1981)</li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Carroll, John M. (1990). <i>The Nurnberg Funnel - Designing Minimalist Instruction for Practical Computer Skill</i>. MIT.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Nurnberg+Funnel+-+Designing+Minimalist+Instruction+for+Practical+Computer+Skill&amp;rft.pub=MIT&amp;rft.date=1990&amp;rft.au=Carroll%2C+John+M.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMinimalism+%28technical+communication%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Carroll, John M. (1998). <i>Minimalism Beyond the Nurnberg Funnel</i>. MIT.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Minimalism+Beyond+the+Nurnberg+Funnel&amp;rft.pub=MIT&amp;rft.date=1998&amp;rft.au=Carroll%2C+John+M.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMinimalism+%28technical+communication%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Hackos, JoAnn T. &amp; Redish, Janice C. (1998). <i>User and Task Analysis for Interface Design</i>. Wiley.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=User+and+Task+Analysis+for+Interface+Design&amp;rft.pub=Wiley&amp;rft.date=1998&amp;rft.au=Hackos%2C+JoAnn+T.&amp;rft.au=Redish%2C+Janice+C.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMinimalism+%28technical+communication%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Brockmann, R. John (1986). <i>Writing Better Computer User Documentation - From Paper to Online</i>. Wiley-Interscience.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Writing+Better+Computer+User+Documentation+-+From+Paper+to+Online&amp;rft.pub=Wiley-Interscience&amp;rft.date=1986&amp;rft.au=Brockmann%2C+R.+John&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMinimalism+%28technical+communication%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></spa